{{Coord|37.286233|-80.047535|display=title}} '''Kiwanis Field''' (formerly called Municipal Field)<ref>[http://www.ballparkreviews.com/template2.php?in_name=Salem%20Municipal%20Field&in_city=Salem&in_state=Virginia "Salem Municipal Field"] ''BallparkReviews.com''. Retrieved 2017-04-17.</ref> is a [[ballpark]] in [[Salem, Virginia]] which was opened in 1932. The ballpark has a capacity of 5,000 people and is primarily used for [[baseball]]. Kiwanis Field was the home of a [[Carolina League]] team currently known as the [[Salem Red Sox]];<ref>[http://www.wsls.com/sports/baseball/salem-red-sox/oliver-returns-to-salem-red-sox "Oliver Returns to Salem Red Sox"] ''WSLS NBC 10''. Retrieved 2017-04-17.</ref> at the time, they were the Salem Rebels (which had previously played in the [[Appalachian League]]), Salem Pirates, Salem Redbirds, and Salem Buccaneers. The Salem Avalanche played here briefly in 1995 until they moved to the [[Salem Memorial Baseball Stadium]]. The stadium has commanding views of the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]], particularly [[Twelve O'clock Knob (Roanoke County, Virginia)|Twelve O'clock Knob]]. Until the [[Salem Football Stadium]] opened in 1985, Kiwanis Field served as the home football field for [[Salem High School (Salem, Virginia)|Salem High School]] and its predecessor Andrew Lewis High School. The stadium was known as Salem Municipal Field prior to 1995.<ref>[https://salemva.gov/Departments/Parks-and-Recreation/Complexes/Kiwanis "Kiwanis"] City of Salem Parks and Recreation. Retrieved 2017-04-17.</ref> Kiwanis Field is currently used for high school, [[American Legion]], and [[Roanoke College]] baseball games.<ref>[http://www.roanoke.com/sports/high_schools/glenvar-overcomes-five-errors-to-advance-in-a-west-baseball/article_9150ed5a-6960-59ff-bfdd-62b4e08e036c.html "Glenvar overcomes five errors to advance in 2A West baseball tournament"] ''Roanoke Times''. Retrieved 2017-04-17.</ref>
